## The Problem

When you define a component **inside another component's render**, React sees it as a **new component type** on every render, unmounts the old one, and mounts a fresh one — destroying focus.

```jsx
// ❌ BROKEN - InputComponent is redefined on every render
function Parent() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');

  // This creates a NEW component type every render cycle
  const InputComponent = () => (
    <input
      value={value}
      onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)}
    />
  );

  return <InputComponent />; // Unmounts/remounts every keystroke
}
```

### Why This Happens

```
Keystroke → setValue() → Parent re-renders
→ New InputComponent function reference created
→ React sees different component type at same position
→ Unmount old tree → Mount new tree → Focus lost
```

---

## The Fixes

### Fix 1: Move the component definition outside (Best Solution)

```jsx
// ✅ CORRECT - Defined once, stable component type
const InputComponent = ({ value, onChange }) => (
  <input value={value} onChange={onChange} />
);

function Parent() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');

  return (
    <InputComponent
      value={value}
      onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
}
```

### Fix 2: Render JSX directly instead of a nested component

```jsx
// ✅ CORRECT - No nested component, just inline JSX
function Parent() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');

  return (
    <input
      value={value}
      onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
}
```

### Fix 3: If you need dynamic components, use `useMemo` on the element (not the component)

```jsx
// ✅ Memoize the element, not the component definition
function Parent() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');
  const [otherState, setOtherState] = useState(false);

  // Stable component defined outside (still required)
  return (
    <div>
      {otherState && <HeavyComponent />}
      <StableInput value={value} onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Fix 4: When you genuinely need a factory pattern, use `useCallback` — but note this still breaks

```jsx
// ⚠️ useCallback does NOT fix this — component type is still unstable
// React compares component constructors, not just references in this context
function Parent() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');

  // Still broken - component defined inside, even if memoized
  const InputComponent = useCallback(
    () => <input value={value} onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)} />,
    [value]
  );

  return <InputComponent />; // Still remounts when value changes
}
```

